<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-01-15T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-01-15T13:00:00-05:00" n="371" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d371">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 860c.20/7:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate
                                    Peace</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                                </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-01-15T13:00:00-05:00">January 15, 1919—1 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received January 16—3:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>236. Department’s 81, January 3rd reads: “Poles are apparently beginning
                            hostilities against Germans.”</p>
                        <p>Does not this reading obviate the inquiry made in your 212, January
                            9th?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>